04054nam a22006255i 9780226509150DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265091507 a10.7208/97802265091502doi  a(DE-B1597)524996  a(OCoLC)1011587767  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aCB158b.P54 2018 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a330.973001122231 aPietruska, Jamie L., eauthor.10aLooking Forward :bPrediction and Uncertainty in Modern America /cJamie L. Pietruska. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b22 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Cotton Guesses -- tChapter 2. The Daily "Probabilities" -- tChapter 3. Weather Prophecies -- tChapter 4. Economies of the Future -- tChapter 5. Promises of Love and Money -- tEpilogue. Specters of Uncertainty -- tArchival Collections -- tPrimary Source Databases -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades after the Civil War, the world experienced monumental changes in industry, trade, and governance. As Americans faced this uncertain future, public debate sprang up over the accuracy and value of predictions, asking whether it was possible to look into the future with any degree of certainty. In Looking Forward, Jamie L. Pietruska uncovers a culture of prediction in the modern era, where forecasts became commonplace as crop forecasters, "weather prophets," business forecasters, utopian novelists, and fortune-tellers produced and sold their visions of the future. Private and government forecasters competed for authority-as well as for an audience-and a single prediction could make or break a forecaster's reputation.  Pietruska argues that this late nineteenth-century quest for future certainty had an especially ironic consequence: it led Americans to accept uncertainty as an inescapable part of both forecasting and twentieth-century economic and cultural life. Drawing together histories of science, technology, capitalism, environment, and culture, Looking Forward explores how forecasts functioned as new forms of knowledge and risk management tools that sometimes mitigated, but at other times exacerbated, the very uncertainties they were designed to conquer. Ultimately Pietruska shows how Americans came to understand the future itself as predictable, yet still uncertain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEconomic forecastingzUnited States. 0aForecastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRiskzUnited States. 4acrop forecasting. 4aeconomic forecasting. 4aforecasting. 4afortune-telling. 4afuture. 4aknowledge production. 4aprediction. 4arisk management. 4auncertainty. 4aweather forecasting. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226509150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226509150.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles